 "target_response": {
  "text": "HRV is heart rate variability: the tiny variations in time between one heartbeat and the next. Counterintuitively, more variability is generally the better sign; it suggests your nervous system is in a rested, adaptable state, while a drop below your personal norm often shows up after hard training, poor sleep, alcohol, or oncoming illness. It's useful precisely because it's compared against your own baseline rather than anyone else's. The reason it's missing from your stats is simple: measuring it requires a device sampling your heartbeat overnight, and you're currently logging everything manually, so there's no HRV, resting heart rate, or recovery score in your data. What you do have is sleep, like last night's 369 minutes, about 6.2 hours. If you want HRV, any tracker worn overnight will start building a baseline within a few weeks.",
